    body: "Adult day care is a daytime program for older adults who need supervision, social contact, or some medical attention during the hours when family caregivers are at work, running errands, or in need of a break. A typical center opens around 7 or 8 in the morning, serves a hot breakfast and lunch, runs activities like music, light exercise, crafts, and group games, has a nurse on site to give medications and check blood pressure, and closes around 5 or 6 in the evening when family members pick the loved one back up. For an adult child caring for a parent with mild to moderate dementia, or a spouse caring for a partner after a stroke, adult day care can be the single most useful resource in the United States that families never hear about until a social worker mentions it.\n\nThere are about 5,000 adult day care centers in the country in 2026, serving roughly 300,000 older adults and disabled adults each day. The cost ranges from about $80 to $120 per day in most areas, paid privately or through Medicaid, Veterans benefits, or long-term care insurance. Compared to in-home aides at $25 to $35 per hour or assisted living at $5,000 a month, adult day care is one of the most affordable forms of professional care. Federal funding through the Older Americans Act subsidizes many centers, especially those that serve lower-income families.\n\nThere are two main types of adult day care centers. The first is social adult day care, which focuses on activities, meals, and companionship for older adults who do not need much medical care. The second is adult day health care (sometimes called adult day services or medical model day care), which adds skilled nursing, physical therapy, occupational therapy, and case management for older adults with significant medical needs like diabetes, congestive heart failure, or moderate dementia. Pick the type that matches your loved one's needs. Some centers offer both under one roof.\n\nThis guide walks through how to find centers near you, what questions to ask before you tour, what to look for during the tour, how to handle the first few days, and how to pay. Bring a notebook and a friend or sibling to the tours so you have two sets of eyes and ears. Start the search two to four weeks before you actually need the care, because most centers have a short waitlist and an assessment process that takes a few days. Use this guide alongside conversations with your loved one's doctor and any social worker assigned to your family.",
